2. Rhescuporim. The orthography of this name varies even on coins, and still more so in the MSS. of various authors: see Lips. and Walther.

Thraeciae. On the form, cp. e. 54, 2. In Roman times the boundary be- tween this country and Macedonia was the Nestus (Karasu). Thrace had been fully subject to Rome for some time, the

. last rising having been crushed in 743,

B. C. 11 (see note on 6. 10, 4), but re- mained under native princes until Claudius made it a province in 799, A. D. 46: see Marquardt, Staatsv. i. p. 156, and a dis- sertation on this dynasty by Mommsen (Eph. Epig. ii. pp. 250 263).

3. Rhoemetalces, the first of that name, son ofSadala and Polemocratia (Momms.). He bears the head of Augustus on the obverse of his coins, in token of suzerainty, and his own on the reverse only, a practice followed by others of this dynasty: see Mr. Donne, in Diet. of Biog. Mommsen (l. l. p. 254) dates his death about 765, A.D. 12, before the composition of Ov. ex P. 2. 9.
